03883nam a22006975i 9781442628090DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426280907 a10.3138/97814426280902doi  a(DE-B1597)496937  a(OCoLC)1076396648  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDT443.3.I83bS35 2008 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.896/390678261 aSanders, Todd, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Bodies :bRain-making and Sense-making in Tanzania /cTodd Sanders. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnthropological Horizons00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tLanguage and Orthography -- tIntroduction: Rainmaking, Gender Epistemologies, and Explanation -- t1. Ihanzu Everyday Worlds -- t2. The Making and Unmaking of Rains and Reigns -- t3. Gendered Life-Worlds and Transformative Processes -- t4. Annual Rain Rites -- t5. (Wo)men Behaving Badly: Genders within Bodies -- t6. Ancestral Rain Offerings: Genders without Bodies -- t7. Witchcraft, Gender, and Inversion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over a century, the Ihanzu of north-central Tanzania have conducted rainmaking rites. As with similar rites found across sub-Saharan Africa, these rites are replete with gender, sexual, and fertility motifs. Social scientists have typically explained such things as symbolizing human bodies and the act of procreation. But what happens when our interlocutors deny such symbolic explanations, when they insist that rain rites and the gender and sexual motifs in them do not symbolize anything but rather aim simply to bring rain?Beyond Bodies examines Ihanzu sensibilities about gender through a fine-grained ethnography of rainmaking rites. It considers the meaning of ritual practices in a society in which gender is not as bound to the body as it is in the Euro-American imagination. Engaging with recent anthropological and gender theory, this book crucially calls into question how social scientists have explained gender symbolism in myriad ethnographic and historical studies across Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIsanzu (African people)xRites and ceremonies. 0aRain-making riteszTanzaniazIramba District. 0aSex rolezTanzaniazIramba District. 0aSocial epistemology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262809040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442628090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442628090.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK